Chapter 10 Gradient Boosting Machines (GBMs)¶

Gradient Boosting Machines (GBMs) are a powerful ensemble machine learning technique widely used for both regression and classification tasks. GBMs work by sequentially combining many weak learners to create a strong predictive model. At each step, a new model is trained to correct the errors (residuals) of the previous models by following the negative gradient of a chosen loss function.

GBMs can be implemented with a variety of base learners, including tree-based models as well as non-tree models such as linear models, neural networks, and support vector machines. However, in practice, tree-based implementations are by far the most popular and effective, due to their flexibility in capturing nonlinear relationships and interactions, and their robustness to data preprocessing requirements. Therefore, when we refer to GBMs in modern applications, we typically mean tree-based gradient boosting ensembles.

How They Work

The GBM algorithm operates in a sequential manner, where each model in the sequence learns from the residuals or gradients of the loss function from previous models. The central idea is to focus on what the current model gets wrong, gradually improving accuracy step-by-step.

Random Forests and Gradient Boosting Machines are both ensemble tree-based methods, but they differ fundamentally in how they learn from data. Random Forests build many deep, fully-grown trees in parallel, and aggregate their predictions through averaging or voting. This strategy primarily aims to reduce variance, making Random Forests highly stable, robust to noise, and less prone to overfitting, although they may underfit when modeling highly complex relationships. In contrast, Gradient Boosting Machines (GBMs) build many shallow trees sequentially, where each new tree focuses on correcting the residual errors of the previous ones. This iterative, gradient-based process is designed to reduce bias and capture complex, nonlinear patterns, often achieving higher predictive accuracy. However, GBMs are more sensitive to hyperparameter tuning and can overfit if not properly regularized (e.g., via learning rate, tree depth, and number of trees), and training is typically more computationally intensive due to the sequential nature of boosting.

See https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZFXD6lxm3nE

Step-by-Step GBM Algorithm

Step-by-Step GBM Algorithm

Gradient Boosting = Gradient descent in function space

  • Start with a baseline model
  • Compute pseudo-residuals
  • Fit weak learners to residuals
  • Update model additively
  • Final model = sum of boosted trees

GBM = start simple, then correct errors one small step at a time

Small, weak trees
focusing on residuals
added slowly
powerful, flexible, high-accuracy model

Mathematics behind the Algorithm:

Given training data
$$\{(x_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^n$$
and loss function $L(y, F(x))$, GBM builds the model incrementally so that each new tree fixes what the previous model got wrong.

1. Initialize the Model

Start with a simple prediction.

For regression, choose the constant that minimizes loss: $$ F_0(x) = \arg\min_{c} \sum_{i=1}^n L(y_i, c) $$

For squared loss, this is the mean: $$ F_0(x) = \bar{y} $$

For binary classification, use log-odds: $$ F_0(x) = \log \frac{\hat{p}}{1-\hat{p}}, \quad \hat{p} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n y_i $$

We start with the best single guess before fitting any trees.

2. Compute Pseudo-Residuals

At iteration $m$, compute the negative gradient of loss: $$ r_{im} = -\left[ \frac{\partial L(y_i, F(x_i))}{\partial F(x_i)} \right]_{F=F_{m-1}} $$

For squared error loss: $$ r_{im} = y_i - F_{m-1}(x_i) $$

Residuals tell us how wrong we are and in what direction. They act like the errors the next tree should learn to correct.

3. Fit a Weak Learner (Shallow Tree)

Train a tree to predict the residuals:

$$ h_m(x) \approx r_{im} $$

Instead of trying to predict $y$ directly, the tree learns how to fix the current mistakes. Each tree = a small correction function.

4. Compute Leaf Values (How Big the Correction Should Be)

For each terminal region $R_{jm}$, $$ \gamma_{jm} = \arg\min_{\gamma} \sum_{x_i \in R_{jm}} L \big( y_i, F_{m-1}(x_i) + \gamma \big) $$

For squared error: $$ \gamma_{jm} = \frac{1}{|R_{jm}|} \sum_{x_i \in R_{jm}} r_{im} $$

Each leaf outputs a small number how much to adjust prediction for samples in that leaf. Not a full prediction just a correction amount.

5. Update the Model

Add scaled tree predictions to prior model:

$$ F_m(x) = F_{m-1}(x) + \nu \sum_{j=1}^{J_m} \gamma_{jm} \mathbf{1}(x \in R_{jm}) $$

where $\nu$ is the learning rate.

Intuition:
We don't trust each tree too much we add a small step in its suggested direction.
Small steps = avoid over-correcting and overfitting.

6. Iterate

Repeat steps 25 for $m = 1, \dots, M$:

$$ r_{im} \Rightarrow h_m(x) \Rightarrow \gamma_{jm} \Rightarrow F_m(x) $$

Intuition:
Boosting is like gradually polishing a model each iteration makes small improvements.
Many weak trees strong final prediction.

7. Final Model

Final boosted model:

$$ F_M(x) = F_0(x) + \sum_{m=1}^{M} \nu \, h_m(x) $$

The final model is the sum of many small correction steps, starting from a simple baseline.

GBM Hyperparameters¶

GBMs have several hyperparameters that can significantly affect their performance. One of the most important is the learning rate, which controls the contribution of each model (tree) to the final prediction. Here's how it works:

  • Smaller learning rate: Requires more trees but can result in a more accurate model.
  • Larger learning rate: Requires fewer trees but may lead to overfitting and less accuracy.

Other important hyperparameters include:

  • Number of iterations (trees): The total number of models to train.
  • Tree depth: Controls the complexity of each individual tree.
  • Subsampling: The fraction of the training data used for each tree, which can help with regularization.
Hyperparameter Typical Range Increases Capacity Helps Regularize Notes
Learning rate (shrinkage, ) 0.010.1 Smaller = slower but better generalization
Number of trees (n.trees / nrounds) 2005000 Tune with early stopping
Tree depth (interaction.depth / max_depth) 18 Controls max interaction order
Min leaf size (n.minobsinnode / min_child_weight) 5100 Larger = smoother model, less variance
Row subsampling (bag.fraction / subsample) 0.50.9 Prevents overfitting, adds randomness
Column subsampling (colsample_bytree / feature_fraction) 0.51.0 Important for high-dimensional data
L2 regularization (lambda / reg_lambda) 010 Stabilizes leaf weights
L1 regularization (alpha / reg_alpha) 010 Produces sparse models, like LASSO
Minimum split gain (gamma / min_gain_to_split) 05 Split only if gain justifies it

R Functions and Examples for GBM Tuning¶

  1. Gradient Boosting with gbm
library(gbm)

set.seed(429)
fit.gbm = gbm(
  formula = y ~ .,
  data = train.dat,
  distribution = "gaussian",     # use "bernoulli" for classification
  n.trees = 5000,                # large upper bound; early stopping will choose best
  interaction.depth = 3,         # tree depth (controls interaction order)
  shrinkage = 0.03,              # learning rate
  n.minobsinnode = 20,           # minimum observations in each leaf
  bag.fraction = 0.7,            # subsampling rate for rows
  train.fraction = 0.8,          # reserve 20% for internal validation
  cv.folds = 5,                  # cross-validation for early stopping
  keep.data = FALSE,
  verbose = FALSE
)

# Pick best number of trees (via CV)
best_iter = gbm.perf(fit.gbm, method = "cv")   # "cv", "OOB", or "test"
best_iter

# Predict on validation set
pred.val = predict(
  fit.gbm,
  newdata = val.dat,
  n.trees = best_iter,
  type = "response"
)

2. Gradient Boosting with caret + XGBoost

library(caret)
set.seed(429)

grid_xgb = expand.grid(
  nrounds = c(500, 1000, 2000),
  max_depth = c(3, 4, 6),
  eta = c(0.03, 0.05, 0.1),           # learning rate
  gamma = c(0, 0.5, 1),              # min loss to split
  colsample_bytree = c(0.7, 0.9),    # feature subsampling
  min_child_weight = c(1, 5),        # minimum leaf weight
  subsample = c(0.7, 0.9)            # row subsampling
)

ctrl = trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 5,
  verboseIter = FALSE
)

fit.xgb = train(
  y ~ .,
  data = train.dat,
  method = "xgbTree",
  trControl = ctrl,
  tuneGrid = grid_xgb,
  metric = "RMSE"
)

fit.xgb$bestTune


3. Gradient Boosting with lightgbm

library(lightgbm)

# Prepare data matrix
dtrain = lgb.Dataset(
  data = as.matrix(train.dat[ , -which(names(train.dat)=="y")]),
  label = train.dat$y
)

params_lgb = list(
  objective = "regression",        # "binary" for classification
  metric = "rmse",
  learning_rate = 0.05,
  num_leaves = 31,                 # leaf complexity  2^(depth)
  max_depth = -1,                  # unlimited tree depth (use num_leaves instead)
  feature_fraction = 0.8,          # column subsampling
  bagging_fraction = 0.8,          # row subsampling
  bagging_freq = 1,
  min_data_in_leaf = 20            # minimum observations per leaf
)

set.seed(429)
fit.lgb = lgb.train(
  params = params_lgb,
  data = dtrain,
  nrounds = 5000,
  valids = list(train = dtrain),   # supply validation set for early stopping in practice
  early_stopping_rounds = 100,
  verbose = 1
)

best_iter = fit.lgb$best_iter

pred.val = predict(
  fit.lgb,
  as.matrix(val.dat[ , -which(names(val.dat)=="y")]),
  n = best_iter
)

Example:

The goal is to build a Gradient Boosting Machine (GBM) model to predict whether an individual has diabetes based on all other available features in the dataset. The dataset description can be found at: https://search.r-project.org/CRAN/refmans/pdp/html/pima.html

Response: diabetes ( Negative or Positive).

A binary classification problem.

data(PimaIndiansDiabetes)
dat = PimaIndiansDiabetes
str(dat)

# Outcome is factor with levels "pos" and "neg" in this dataset.
# caret's twoClassSummary uses the FIRST level of the outcome as the "event"/positive class.
# Ensure "pos" is the first level so ROC reflects predicting "pos".
dat$diabetes = factor(dat$diabetes, levels = c("pos","neg"))
#binary classification

set.seed(252)

index = createDataPartition(dat$diabetes, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train.dat = dat[index,]
test.dat =   dat[-index,]

#Model tuning via R caret train function
set.seed(738)
#mtry : the number of variables to randomly sample as candidates at each split. 
#When mtry = the number of features. the random forest model equates to bagging.

#4 tuning parameters for train fucntion with 'gbm' methods
gbmGrid =  expand.grid( interaction.depth = c(1, 3, 5), 
                        n.trees = seq(5,20,by=5)*50, 
                        shrinkage = c(0.01, 0.02, 0.05),
                        n.minobsinnode = 20)

trcn = trainControl(       method = "cv",
                           number = 10,
                           # repeats = 6,
                           ## Estimate class probabilities
                           classProbs = TRUE,
                           ## Evaluate performance using the following function
                           summaryFunction = twoClassSummary)

#Train a gbm model by selecting the optimal tuning paramter
gbm.fit = train(diabetes ~ ., data = train.dat,
                   method = 'gbm',                   
                   tuneGrid = gbmGrid, 
                   trControl = trcn,
                   metric = "ROC")

In [5]:
# ---------------------------------------------------
# Set up GBM tuning grid & trainControl
#    NOTE: These are GBM parameters (NOT Random Forest/mtry).
# ---------------------------------------------------
# interaction.depth: tree depth (controls interaction order)
# n.trees          : total boosting iterations
# shrinkage        : learning rate
# n.minobsinnode   : min observations per leaf
gbmGrid = expand.grid(
  interaction.depth = c(1, 3, 5, 9),
  n.trees = seq(5, 20, by=5) * 50,        # from 250 to 1000
  shrinkage = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1),
  n.minobsinnode = c(10, 20, 40)
)

# 10-fold CV, evaluate ROC; classProbs=TRUE required for ROC
trcn = trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 10,
  classProbs = TRUE,
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
  verboseIter = FALSE
)

# ---------------------------------------------------
#Train GBM model (optimize ROC)
# ---------------------------------------------------
set.seed(738)
gbm.fit = train(
  diabetes ~ .,
  data = train.dat,
  method = "gbm",
  trControl = trcn,
  tuneGrid = gbmGrid,
  metric = "ROC",
  verbose = FALSE
)

# Best tuning parameters
gbm.fit$bestTune
plot(gbm.fit)  # CV profile (optional)

# ---------------------------------------------------
# Evaluate on the test set
# ---------------------------------------------------
# Class probabilities (second column corresponds to "pos" probability if levels set as above)
prob.pos = predict(gbm.fit, newdata = test.dat, type = "prob")[, "pos"]
pred.cls = predict(gbm.fit, newdata = test.dat)

# Confusion matrix (explicitly set positive class = "pos")
confusionMatrix(pred.cls, test.dat$diabetes, positive = "pos")

# ROC & AUC
roc.obj = roc(response = test.dat$diabetes, predictor = prob.pos, levels = c("neg","pos"))
plot(roc.obj, main = "ROC Curve - GBM (PimaIndiansDiabetes)")
auc(roc.obj)

Sensitivity (also called true positive rate) measures how well the model catches people who actually have diabetes.

Specificity (also called true negative rate) measures how well the model identifies people who do not have diabetes.

The ROC curve shows how good the model is at separating positive cases from negative cases. the ROC curve helps us compare models and choose the best threshold for making decisions.

The curve rises steeply toward the upper-left corner, showing that the model effectively distinguishes between diabetic and non-diabetic individuals across various threshold settings. Visually, the area under the curve (AUC) appears to be high (likely in the 0.850.90 range), demonstrating that the model performs far better than random guessing. In medical screening contexts such as diabetes detection, this shape reflects a desirable trade-off, with high sensitivity achieved while maintaining good specificity. Overall, the ROC curve suggests that the GBM model is a strong predictive tool for identifying individuals at risk for diabetes in this dataset.

# Model training using the caret package : train function
set.seed(295)

#Cross validation :  7 fold cross validaiton
ctrl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 7)

# hyper-parameters:  ....
gbmGrid =  expand.grid(interaction.depth = c(6, 9, 12, 15), 
                        n.trees = seq(8, 20, by=4)*50, 
                        shrinkage = c(0.01, 0.05,0.1, 0.2),
                        n.minobsinnode = 20)

#train to find the optimal tuning parameters
n.fit = train(medv ~ ., data = train.dat,  method = "gbm",
                   trControl = ctrl,
                   tuneGrid = gbmGrid,
                   preProc = c("center", "scale")
)

#Using gbm function in package gmb

library(gbm)
set.seed(1213)  # for reproducibility
fit.gbm1 <- gbm(medv ~ ., data = train.dat,
  distribution = "gaussian",  # SSE loss function , regression
  n.trees = 5000,
  shrinkage = 0.01,
  interaction.depth = 3,
  n.minobsinnode = 10,
  cv.folds = 10
)

# find index for number trees with minimum CV error
best <- which.min(fit.gbm1$cv.error)

# get MSE and compute RMSE
sqrt(fit.gbm1$cv.error[best])

#XGBoost
library(caret)
library(xgboost)

grid_xgb = expand.grid(
  nrounds = c(500, 1000, 2000),
  max_depth = c(3, 4, 6),
  eta = c(0.03, 0.05, 0.1),           # learning rate
  gamma = c(0, 0.5, 1),              # min loss to split
  colsample_bytree = c(0.7, 0.9),    # feature subsampling
  min_child_weight = c(1, 5),        # minimum leaf weight
  subsample = c(0.7, 0.9)            # row subsampling
)

ctrl = trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 5,
  verboseIter = FALSE
)

fit.xgb = train(
  medv ~ .,
  data = train.dat,
  method = "xgbTree",
  trControl = ctrl,
  tuneGrid = grid_xgb,
  metric = "RMSE"                  #For regression
)

#Split the data into train set and test set
set.seed(252)

dat = Sonar 

# Convert target to numeric (for gbm: 0/1)
#Sonar$Class <- ifelse(Sonar$Class == "M", 1, 0)
dat$Class = as.numeric(dat $ Class) - 1
#dat$Class 

index = createDataPartition(Sonar$Class, p = 0.75, list = FALSE)
train.dat = dat[index,]
test.dat =   dat[-index,]
In [35]:
#library(gbm)

set.seed(121)
fit.gbm = gbm(
  formula = Class ~ .,
  data = train.dat,
  distribution = "bernoulli",     # use "bernoulli" for classification
  n.trees = 5000,                # large upper bound; early stopping will choose best
  interaction.depth = 3,         # tree depth (controls interaction order)
  shrinkage = 0.03,              # learning rate
  n.minobsinnode = 20,           # minimum observations in each leaf
  bag.fraction = 0.7,            # subsampling rate for rows
  train.fraction = 0.8,          # reserve 20% for internal validation
  cv.folds = 5,                  # cross-validation for early stopping
  keep.data = FALSE,
  verbose = FALSE
)

# Pick best number of trees (via CV)
best_iter = gbm.perf(fit.gbm, method = "cv")   # "cv", "OOB", or "test"
best_iter

# Predict on validation set
pred.val = predict(
  fit.gbm,
  newdata = test.dat,
  n.trees = best_iter,
  type = "response"
)
